-- 3. RSI Divergence
('rsi-divergence-pattern-validation',
'RSI Divergence: Validating Reversal Pattern Signals',
'Discover how RSI divergence confirms or denies reversal patterns like double bottoms, head & shoulders, and wedges.',
E'## Why RSI Matters for Pattern Traders\n\nRSI (Relative Strength Index) measures the speed and magnitude of price changes. For pattern traders, RSI divergence is the single most valuable confirmation tool for reversal patterns.\n\n## How RSI Confirms Reversal Patterns\n\n### Bullish RSI Divergence + Reversal Pattern\n\nWhen price makes a lower low (forming a reversal base like a double bottom) but RSI makes a higher low, momentum is shifting bullish despite lower prices:\n\n- **Double Bottom + Bullish RSI Divergence** = High-probability reversal\n- **Inverse Head & Shoulders + RSI Divergence at right shoulder** = Strong confirmation\n- **Falling Wedge + RSI Divergence** = Breakout likely\n\n### Bearish RSI Divergence + Reversal Pattern\n\nWhen price makes a higher high (forming a reversal top) but RSI makes a lower high:\n\n- **Double Top + Bearish RSI Divergence** = High-probability reversal\n- **Head & Shoulders + RSI Divergence at right shoulder** = Strong confirmation\n- **Rising Wedge + RSI Divergence** = Breakdown likely\n\n### Overbought/Oversold at Pattern Levels\n\n- RSI below 30 at pattern support → Oversold bounce + pattern support = strong long\n- RSI above 70 at pattern resistance → Overbought rejection + pattern resistance = strong short\n\n## Pattern-Specific RSI Usage\n\n### Double Bottom: The Classic RSI Divergence Play\n1. First bottom: RSI drops below 30 (oversold)\n2. Rally: RSI recovers to 40-50\n3. Second bottom: Price makes equal/lower low, RSI makes HIGHER low (still above 30)\n4. This divergence confirms the double bottom — enter on neckline break\n\n### Head & Shoulders\n- Left shoulder: RSI peaks\n- Head: RSI makes lower peak despite higher price\n- Right shoulder: RSI makes even lower peak\n- Progressive RSI divergence across 3 peaks = very high-probability reversal\n\n### Triple Tops/Bottoms\nRSI divergence across all three touches dramatically increases pattern reliability.\n\n## Centerline (50) as Trend Filter\n\n- **RSI above 50 + bullish pattern breakout** = Pattern aligned with momentum\n- **RSI below 50 + bearish pattern breakdown** = Pattern aligned with momentum\n- **RSI opposing pattern direction** = Lower probability, reduce size\n\n## Settings\n\n- **Standard:** 14-period — works for most pattern timeframes\n- **Fast (7-period):** More sensitive, useful for intraday patterns\n- **Slow (21-period):** Smoother, fewer false signals on swing patterns\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Position Size:** 1-2% per trade, increase to 2% when RSI divergence confirms pattern\n- **Stop Loss:** Always based on pattern structure, not RSI levels\n- **Risk-Reward:** Minimum 1:2, target 1:3 when RSI divergence confirms\n- **Max Risk:** 5% total exposure\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Trading RSI divergence alone without a chart pattern context\n- Expecting divergence to work immediately (can persist for bars)\n- Using RSI overbought/oversold as standalone signals in trending markets\n- Ignoring the trend — divergence works best at pattern-defined reversal zones\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nRSI divergence is the "momentum truth serum" for reversal patterns. When a pattern says "reversal" and RSI divergence agrees, you have one of the highest-probability setups in technical analysis.',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'intermediate', 'published', 15,
ARRAY['rsi', 'divergence', 'pattern-confirmation', 'reversal-patterns', 'indicators'],
