-- 5. Fibonacci
('fibonacci-pattern-confluence',
'Fibonacci Retracements: Finding Pattern Confluence Zones',
'Learn how Fibonacci levels create confluence zones with chart patterns for precise entry and target placement.',
E'## Why Fibonacci Matters for Pattern Traders\n\nFibonacci retracement levels identify where pullbacks within patterns are most likely to find support or resistance. When a Fibonacci level aligns with a pattern boundary, you have a **confluence zone** — one of the most reliable entry setups in technical analysis.\n\n## How Fibonacci Confirms Patterns\n\n### Pattern Boundaries at Fibonacci Levels\n\n- **Flag pullback to 38.2-50% retracement** = Shallow, healthy correction in strong trend\n- **Pattern support at 61.8% retracement** = Deep but still valid pullback\n- **Pattern base at 78.6% retracement** = Last defense before trend failure\n\n### Fibonacci Extensions for Pattern Targets\n\n- **127.2% extension** = Conservative pattern breakout target\n- **161.8% extension** = Standard measured move target\n- **200% extension** = Extended target for strong breakouts\n\n## Pattern-Specific Fibonacci Usage\n\n### Bull/Bear Flags\nMeasure the pole, apply Fibonacci. The flag base typically retraces 38.2-50% of the pole. Flags retracing beyond 61.8% are likely failing.\n\n### Cup & Handle\nThe handle typically retraces 38.2-50% of the cup depth. Deeper handles (beyond 61.8%) suggest weakness.\n\n### Head & Shoulders\nThe neckline often aligns with 38.2% or 50% retracement of the entire head-to-shoulder move.\n\n### Triangles & Wedges\nInternal swing points within triangles often respect Fibonacci ratios.\n\n## Key Fibonacci Levels\n\n- **23.6%** — Shallow retracement (very strong trend)\n- **38.2%** — Standard healthy pullback\n- **50.0%** — Psychological midpoint\n- **61.8%** — Golden ratio, critical level\n- **78.6%** — Last chance before trend reversal\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Position Size:** 1-2% risk per trade\n- **Stop Loss:** Below the next Fibonacci level beyond your entry\n- **Risk-Reward:** Fibonacci extensions provide natural targets (1:2 to 1:3)\n- **Max Risk:** 5% total exposure\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Drawing Fibonacci on wrong swing points\n- Treating every Fibonacci level as support (context matters)\n- Ignoring pattern structure in favor of Fibonacci alone\n- Using Fibonacci on choppy, range-bound price action\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nFibonacci doesn''t predict — it identifies where pattern boundaries are most likely to hold. The intersection of a chart pattern boundary and a Fibonacci level is where you want to be taking trades.',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'intermediate', 'published', 14,
ARRAY['fibonacci', 'pattern-confirmation', 'confluence', 'retracement', 'indicators'],
'Fibonacci Retracements for Pattern Confluence | ChartingPath',
'Learn how Fibonacci levels create confluence zones with chart patterns for precise entry and target placement.',
