-- 6. Support & Resistance
('support-resistance-pattern-structure',
'Support & Resistance: The Foundation of Pattern Structure',
'Understand how support and resistance levels define chart pattern boundaries and create high-probability trade zones.',
E'## Why S/R Matters for Pattern Traders\n\nEvery chart pattern is built on support and resistance. A double bottom IS two tests of support. A head and shoulders IS resistance at the neckline. Understanding S/R is understanding the DNA of patterns.\n\n## How S/R Defines Patterns\n\n### Pattern Boundaries = S/R Levels\n\n- **Double Bottom/Top:** Horizontal support/resistance tested twice\n- **Head & Shoulders:** Neckline is the critical S/R level\n- **Triangles:** Converging S/R trendlines\n- **Flags:** Parallel S/R channels within a trend\n- **Wedges:** Converging S/R with directional bias\n\n### S/R Quality = Pattern Quality\n\nStronger S/R levels produce more reliable patterns:\n\n- **Multiple Touches:** Level tested 2-3+ times = stronger pattern\n- **Higher Timeframe Visibility:** Pattern at weekly S/R > daily S/R\n- **Volume Confirmation:** High volume at tests = strong interest\n- **Confluence:** Multiple S/R types align = highest quality\n\n## Types of S/R in Pattern Context\n\n- **Horizontal S/R:** Static levels from prior highs/lows — defines double tops/bottoms\n- **Dynamic S/R:** Moving averages (20, 50, 200 EMA) — often aligns with pattern boundaries\n- **Trendline S/R:** Diagonal lines connecting swing points — defines triangles and wedges\n- **Psychological S/R:** Round numbers — adds confluence to pattern levels\n- **Fibonacci S/R:** Retracement levels — aligns with pattern pullback zones\n\n## Zones vs. Lines\n\nProfessional traders think in **zones**, not exact lines:\n\n- Mark S/R as a zone spanning recent wicks\n- Zone width: Typically 0.5-1% of price\n- Pattern confirmation should occur within or at the zone edge\n- This accounts for market noise and prevents premature entries\n\n## S/R Polarity (Role Reversal)\n\nBroken support becomes resistance, and vice versa:\n\n- **Pattern breakout retest** = Old resistance now supporting as new support\n- This is the basis for "breakout and retest" pattern entries\n- Volume on the retest should be lower than on the breakout\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Stop Loss:** Always beyond the S/R zone (add ATR buffer)\n- **Position Size:** 1-2% per trade\n- **Risk-Reward:** Target next S/R level for TP (minimum 1:2)\n- **Max Risk:** 5% total exposure\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Drawing too many levels (creates analysis paralysis)\n- Using exact price lines instead of zones\n- Ignoring higher timeframe S/R levels\n- Trading weak levels with only 1 touch\n- Not waiting for candlestick confirmation at levels\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nYou don''t need to "add" S/R analysis to pattern trading — **pattern trading IS S/R trading**. The better you understand support and resistance, the better you''ll identify and trade chart patterns.',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'beginner', 'published', 12,
ARRAY['support-resistance', 'pattern-confirmation', 'price-action', 'structure', 'indicators'],
