-- 7. Breakout Trading
('breakout-pattern-execution',
'Breakout Trading: Executing Chart Pattern Breakouts',
'Master the mechanics of entering and managing breakout trades from validated chart patterns.',
E'## The Breakout is Where Patterns Pay Off\n\nChart pattern analysis identifies the setup — the breakout is the execution. This guide covers how to trade breakouts from validated chart patterns with precision.\n\n## Types of Pattern Breakouts\n\n### Continuation Breakouts\nFrom patterns that form within existing trends:\n- **Bull/Bear Flags:** Breakout in trend direction after consolidation\n- **Pennants:** Symmetrical consolidation followed by trend continuation\n- **Cup & Handle:** Handle breakout above cup resistance\n\n### Reversal Breakouts\nFrom patterns that signal trend changes:\n- **Double Bottom:** Breakout above neckline\n- **Head & Shoulders:** Breakdown below neckline\n- **Wedges:** Breakout against the wedge direction\n\n## Breakout Confirmation Criteria\n\nNot all breakouts are equal. Filter for quality:\n\n1. **Volume Surge:** Breakout volume should be 50%+ above average\n2. **Candle Close:** Price should CLOSE beyond the pattern boundary (not just wick)\n3. **Momentum Alignment:** MACD, RSI should support the breakout direction\n4. **Prior Trend:** Continuation patterns need a qualifying prior trend\n5. **Pattern Quality:** A/B grade patterns from the detection engine\n\n## Entry Strategies\n\n### Aggressive Entry\nEnter on the breakout candle close beyond the pattern boundary.\n- Pro: Catches the full move\n- Con: Higher false breakout risk\n\n### Conservative Entry (Retest)\nWait for breakout, then enter on pullback retest of the broken level.\n- Pro: Better entry price, confirmation of S/R flip\n- Con: May miss strong breakouts that don''t retest\n\n### Scaled Entry\nEnter 50% on breakout, 50% on retest.\n- Pro: Balanced approach\n- Con: Average entry price may be suboptimal\n\n## Measured Move Targets\n\n- **Flags/Pennants:** Height of the pole projected from breakout point\n- **Triangles:** Width of the triangle base projected from breakout\n- **Double Bottom/Top:** Height of the pattern projected from neckline\n- **H&S:** Distance from head to neckline projected from neckline break\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Stop Loss:** Just inside the pattern boundary (opposite side of breakout)\n- **Position Size:** 1-2% risk per trade\n- **Risk-Reward:** Minimum 1:2 using measured move targets\n- **Max Risk:** 6% total portfolio exposure on breakout trades\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Chasing breakouts without waiting for candle close confirmation\n- Ignoring volume on breakout (low-volume breakouts often fail)\n- Not having a clear measured move target before entering\n- Using stops too tight (getting stopped by normal retest volatility)\n- Trading breakouts from low-quality pattern formations\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nPattern identification is only half the battle — breakout execution determines your profitability. Use volume, momentum confirmation, and measured move targets to transform pattern signals into profitable trades.',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'intermediate', 'published', 15,
ARRAY['breakout', 'pattern-confirmation', 'execution', 'volume', 'indicators'],
'Breakout Trading from Chart Patterns | ChartingPath',
