-- 13. Position Trading
('position-trading-pattern-strategies',
'Position Trading: Long-Term Pattern Setups on Weekly Charts',
'Identify and trade weekly chart patterns for position trades lasting weeks to months.',
E'## Chart Patterns on Weekly Charts\n\nPosition trading uses weekly and monthly chart patterns for trades lasting weeks to months. These patterns are rare but extremely reliable because they represent major market structure shifts.\n\n## Why Weekly Patterns Are More Reliable\n\n- **More data per candle:** Each weekly candle aggregates 5 days of price action\n- **Less noise:** Random intraday movements are filtered out\n- **Institutional footprints:** Weekly patterns reflect major capital flow decisions\n- **Higher volume confirmation:** Breakout volume on weekly charts is definitive\n\n## Best Position Trading Patterns\n\n### Major Reversal Patterns (Weekly)\n- **Head & Shoulders:** Major trend reversal over 3-6 months\n- **Double Bottom/Top:** Macro support/resistance failure\n- **Cup & Handle:** Multi-month accumulation pattern\n- **Triple Top/Bottom:** Extended distribution/accumulation\n\n### Major Continuation Patterns (Weekly)\n- **Bull/Bear Flags on weekly:** Multi-week consolidation in strong trends\n- **Ascending/Descending Triangles:** Multi-month institutional accumulation\n- **Symmetrical Triangles:** Extended consolidation before macro breakout\n\n## Confirmation for Position Trades\n\n1. **Monthly trend direction** — position patterns should align with monthly trend\n2. **200-week moving average** — is pattern above (bullish) or below (bearish)?\n3. **Monthly RSI** — is there divergence supporting the pattern?\n4. **Sector/index correlation** — is the broader market supporting the move?\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Position Size:** 0.5-1% risk per trade (wider stops = smaller positions)\n- **Stop Loss:** Below/above pattern boundary with multi-week ATR buffer\n- **Risk-Reward:** Minimum 1:3, often 1:5 to 1:10 on major patterns\n- **Max Exposure:** 5% total portfolio in position trades\n- **Scaling:** Enter 1/3 at breakout, 1/3 on retest, 1/3 on confirmation\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Trying to position trade with daily chart patterns (too small)\n- Impatience — weekly patterns take months to develop and break\n- Under-sizing because stops are wide (position size should account for this)\n- Ignoring macro context (Fed policy, earnings seasons, etc.)\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nPosition trading patterns are rare, but when they appear on weekly charts, they offer the highest R:R opportunities in trading. Patience is the primary skill.',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'advanced', 'published', 14,
ARRAY['position-trading', 'weekly-patterns', 'pattern-confirmation', 'long-term', 'indicators'],
'Position Trading with Weekly Chart Patterns | ChartingPath',
'Identify and trade weekly chart patterns for position trades lasting weeks to months.',
