-- 14. Mean Reversion
('mean-reversion-pattern-context',
'Mean Reversion: When Patterns Signal Return to Equilibrium',
'Understand how mean reversion principles apply to chart pattern entries at extreme price levels.',
E'## Mean Reversion in Pattern Context\n\nMean reversion — the tendency of price to return to its average — is the underlying force behind reversal patterns. Every double bottom, head & shoulders, and wedge reversal is essentially a mean reversion event.\n\n## How Mean Reversion Powers Reversal Patterns\n\n### The Rubber Band Effect\n\nWhen price extends far from its mean (moving average), the probability of reversion increases:\n\n- **Price 2+ standard deviations from 20 SMA** = Extended, reversal pattern likely to work\n- **Price near the mean** = Neutral, continuation patterns may be better plays\n- **Bollinger Band touch + reversal pattern** = High-probability mean reversion setup\n\n## Mean Reversion Indicators for Pattern Confirmation\n\n### RSI Extremes\n- RSI below 30 at pattern support → Oversold + pattern = strong reversion signal\n- RSI above 70 at pattern resistance → Overbought + pattern = strong reversion signal\n\n### Bollinger Band Position\n- Price at lower band + double bottom = Mean reversion entry\n- Price at upper band + double top = Mean reversion entry\n\n### Distance from Moving Average\n- Measure % distance from 20 SMA or 50 SMA\n- Historically extreme distances increase reversal pattern success\n\n## Best Patterns for Mean Reversion\n\n1. **Double Bottoms at Bollinger lower band** = Classic\n2. **Double Tops at Bollinger upper band** = Classic\n3. **Falling Wedge at oversold extremes** = High probability\n4. **Rising Wedge at overbought extremes** = High probability\n5. **H&S at distance from 200 MA** = Major mean reversion\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Position Size:** 1-2% per trade\n- **Stop Loss:** Beyond the extreme (if mean reversion fails, trend is dominant)\n- **Risk-Reward:** 1:2 minimum (target the mean itself)\n- **Scaling:** Enter 50% at pattern signal, 50% on confirmation\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Mean reversion in strong trends (trends can stay extended longer than expected)\n- Not using pattern structure (mean reversion alone has poor win rate)\n- Setting targets beyond the mean (the mean IS the target)\n- Fighting momentum with mean reversion plays\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nMean reversion is most powerful when combined with pattern structure. A reversal pattern at an extreme price level is one of the highest-probability setups in technical analysis.',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'intermediate', 'published', 12,
ARRAY['mean-reversion', 'pattern-confirmation', 'reversal', 'bollinger', 'indicators'],
'Mean Reversion in Pattern Context | ChartingPath',
'Understand how mean reversion principles apply to chart pattern entries at extreme price levels.',
now()),

-- 15. Gap Trading
('gap-trading-pattern-context',
'Gap Trading: Patterns Around Price Gaps',
'Learn how chart patterns form around price gaps and how to trade gap-fill and gap-continuation setups.',
E'## Gaps and Chart Patterns\n\nPrice gaps create instant support/resistance levels. When chart patterns form around these gap levels, they produce some of the most reliable trade setups.\n\n## Types of Gaps in Pattern Context\n\n### Breakaway Gaps\n- Occur at pattern breakout points\n- **Bull Flag breakout + upside gap** = Very strong continuation signal\n- **H&S neckline break + downside gap** = Strong reversal confirmation\n- Breakaway gaps rarely fill — don''t fade them\n\n### Exhaustion Gaps\n- Occur at pattern completion/failure points\n- **Gap at the end of a trend after extended move** = Reversal pattern may form\n- **Gap followed by bearish engulfing** = Island reversal pattern\n- Exhaustion gaps often fill — trade the fill as mean reversion\n\n### Common Gaps\n- Occur within patterns during formation\n- **Gap within triangle consolidation** = Noise, not significant\n- **Gap within flag** = Normal, doesn''t invalidate pattern\n\n## Gap + Pattern Setups\n\n### Gap and Go (Continuation)\n1. Stock gaps up through resistance\n2. Forms a tight flag/pennant after the gap\n3. Breakout from flag = continuation of gap momentum\n4. Volume should remain high post-gap\n\n### Gap Fill + Pattern (Reversion)\n1. Stock gaps but starts to fill\n2. Pattern forms at the gap fill level\n3. Double bottom at gap support = Mean reversion entry\n4. Target: Return to gap top\n\n### Island Reversal (Exhaustion)\n1. Gap up at trend extreme\n2. One or more candles trade above the gap\n3. Gap down back below — creating an "island" of price\n4. This IS a reversal pattern — treat it as such\n\n## Confirmation for Gap Trades\n\n- **Volume:** Gap breakouts need 2x+ average volume\n- **Time:** First 30 minutes after gap = volatile, wait for pattern to form\n- **Pre-market levels:** Gaps that hold pre-market highs/lows are stronger\n- **Sector alignment:** Gaps in direction of sector trend are more reliable\n\n## Risk Management\n\n- **Position Size:** 1-2% per trade (gaps can be volatile)\n- **Stop Loss:** Below the gap zone for gap-and-go, above gap for gap fills\n- **Risk-Reward:** 1:2 minimum\n- **Gap Rule:** Never fade a breakaway gap from a quality pattern\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n- Fading all gaps (breakaway gaps don''t fill)\n- Trading gaps without pattern structure\n- Chasing gaps without waiting for consolidation pattern\n- Ignoring pre-market context and volume\n\n## Key Takeaway\n\nGaps create instant S/R levels. When chart patterns form around these levels, they produce high-probability setups. The key is identifying whether the gap is a breakaway (trade continuation) or exhaustion (trade reversal).',
'Indicator Guides', 'Pattern Confirmation', 'article', 'intermediate', 'published', 13,
ARRAY['gap-trading', 'pattern-confirmation', 'breakaway-gap', 'island-reversal', 'indicators'],
'Gap Trading with Chart Patterns | ChartingPath',
